messages.content: @joe_palermo The way I see it Bittensor is build a representational base for AI, essentially turning GPT3 into an internet rather than a single model.

This is Chollet's work. A lot of research here was inspired by him. However, his main thesis is that we need to build a measure of intelligence based on a model's ability to learn new tasks. We see it rather as building a measure of intelligence based on other intelligence systems.
The best measure of intelligence is intelligence itself.

Question about the whitepaper. Regarding W_dg, I see d is depth but what is g? Also how does the indexing scheme over W work? 

If W is simply constructed at each point in time by the weights from each peer, how do you index using d? I take it that W_dg != w_dg, i.e. something different is meant by the capital W.
Well I suppose Bittensor treats intelligence in information theoretic terms. I.e. how useful are an agent's representations in producing accurate predictions.
As measured by other agents

I think Chollet would refer to that as the estimation of "crystallized skill" in a particular domain. I think it's a good objective to use actually, since skill is ultimately what is of value to others.

What was interesting to me about Chollet's work is that he introduces efficiency and priors into the discussion about intelligence. "The intelligence of a system is a measure of skill-acquisition efficiency over a scope of tasks, with respect to priors, experience, and generalization difficulty." To me this was very helpful way of framing things.
dg is the diagonal matrix, this is a tad obtuse I agree
(W - Wdg)^k is an absorbing markov chain step
On this topic however, we have found it simpler to replace the matrix C with a simple threshold over the value with some cut off kappa
The use of the markov chain adds complexity we don't need right now.
I've never heard of this term "crystallized skill". Does he mean to say that because the domain is fixed, that the skill is fixed?

It seems to me that you can nest "The intelligence of a system is a measure of skill-acquisition efficiency over a scope of tasks, with respect to priors, experience, and generalization difficulty." within the larger domain of survival in an environment which is changing. Thus if the domain is fixed to the world as it is, it demands the ability to adapt to new skills, you would actually see that the fixed becomes the adaptive and vice versa.
Put another way, the task which is all tasks at sometime or the other, would actually be a proxy for skill-acquisition
yes I think that's fair. The evolutionary environment in which intelligence evolved was highly dynamic and so the capability to quickly adapt (i.e. efficiently learn new skills) was rewarded.

Chollet uses this term "crystallized" in his Measure of Intelligence paper and it comes from the psychology literature. He distinguishes "crystallized skill on one hand, skill- acquisition ability on the other". So it refers to skills which are fixed.

For example someone could be highly skilled but a slow learner because they had a long time to learn it.
Or vice versa, not very skilled but a fast learner
I guess the question is: which is the proxy?
Chollet's skill acquisition benchmark or the set-of-all-tasks task

Further question, regardless of the directionality of the proxy, which is the best way of measuring intelligence? (which will induce its creation faster) Creating skill acquisition measures or pilling together all tasks into a single benchmark.

It's an interesting question. If you were going to have a single ultimate benchmark it would have to include tasks such as ARC which require generalizing from few examples. So to succeed on the set-of-all-tasks task you would have to have high learning efficiency.
Does the set-of-all-tasks that aren't compressed proxies of themselves contain itself?
jk
It does raise a very good point, because technically, I think, if you did have the set of all tasks, you would then just have a random function.

Once you do that, your model will start exchanging information (gradients) with other models on the network as it trains on your machine.

This will also enable distributed training, but obviously we'll see the true distributed training benefits only when critical mass is reached -- that is, when enough people are training on the network.
So no, you can't schedule a job or request one this way, but your training will be distributed and decentralized by default when you train on bittensor network anyways.
Short answer no.

The bittensor network provides the feature base for you to train your model on top of. So technically it provides "information" (hidden units of all the other models on your data) not compute power. Obviously, since that information has been trained by compute you are getting it indirectly
If you are thinking of solving a supervised problem on bittensor you are probably out of luck. The goal here is share unsupervised representations.
However, your supervised problem probably first depends on an unsupervised feature space to get good accuracy (i.e. image/video understanding for your RL case)

messages.content: your model and my model are now talking to each other, exchanging gradients and learning from each other.

their inter-connection is actually a bunch of hidden layers that connect to each other on the internet (bittensor calls the layer that sends information the `dendrite`, and the layer that receives information an `axon`)..
So in connecting together, my model and your model are actually forming one large model over the internet
part GPT2, part GPTNeo
Now both of us are running Bittensor, which means that each our models is also training a small, distilled version of the inter-connected network.
In other words, a smaller compressed model that imitates the big GPT2<>GPTNeo model over the internet

now for incentivization, the question becomes "are you useful to me".. if your GPT2 is useful to my GPTNeo (i.e. it helps me minimize my loss function), then i am more likely to speak to you again, and will reward you with some tao.
Same goes for you. If I am useful to you, you can reward me with some tao. If i am less useful, then reward me less, etc.

i hope this helps 🙂 this is what i mean when i say that indeed models can be "born" on the network. because you now have two different architectures plugged in to each other, and distillation method allows you to get a compressed version of these inter-connected models.

'''
1. Sort the array

    3. Iterate over the array
    4. See if there is a duplicate number.

    :type array: List[int]
    :param array: An array of integers

    :rtype: bool
    :return: True if there is a duplicate number, False otherwise
    """
    duplicate = set()

    # Sort the array
    if len(array) <= 0:
        return False

    if not array:
        return False

    for i in range(len(array)):
        if i > 0 and array[i - 1] == array[i - 2]:

    if array[0] in duplicate:
        return True

    duplicate.add(array[0])

    return False
